      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The classic case of a memory leak, reminiscent of the infamous \"Goblin's Gold\" scenario, where a mischievous goblin steals all the gold from the kingdom, leaving nothing but a trail of glittering dust. In this case, the goblin is your code, and it's not releasing the memory allocated for the `dataBuffer`.\n\nThe issue lies in the fact that you're not checking for errors when allocating memory with `new`. If the allocation fails, `new` will return `nullptr`, but you're not handling this case. When you try to delete `nullptr`, you'll get a segmentation fault, which will lead to a device crash.\n\nTo fix this, you should check the return value of `new` and handle the error case:\n\n```cpp\nvoid processSensorData(int sensorId) {\n    int* dataBuffer = new (std::nothrow) int[100];\n    \n    if (dataBuffer == nullptr) {\n        // handle allocation error, e.g., log an error message\n        return;\n    }\n\n    if (sensorId < 0) {\n        delete[] dataBuffer;\n        return; \n    }\n\n    for (int i = 0; i < 100; ++i)",
