      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the actual issue.\n\nThe main problem with your code is that you're allocating memory for `dataBuffer` in every single call to `processSensorData`, regardless of the value of `sensorId`. This means that the memory is being allocated and deallocated repeatedly, but the memory itself is not being freed.\n\nThe reason you're seeing the heap grow is because the memory is not being freed. Each time you call `processSensorData`, a new block of memory is allocated, but the old block is not being deallocated. This is why the heap is growing.\n\nTo fix this, you should allocate the memory once and reuse it. You can do this by moving the allocation outside the function and passing a pointer to it as an argument. Here's an example:\n\n```cpp\nint* dataBuffer = nullptr;\n\nvoid processSensorData(int sensorId) {\n    if (dataBuffer == nullptr) {\n        dataBuffer = new (std::nothrow) int[100];\n        if (dataBuffer == nullptr) {\n            // handle allocation error\n            return;\n        }\n    }\n\n    if (sensorId < 0) {\n        delete[] dataBuffer;",
