      "content": "You are correct that moving the allocation outside the function and not deleting it elsewhere would lead to memory leaks and other issues.\n\nRegarding your original code, the issue is not with the `sensorId` check, but with the fact that you're allocating memory for `dataBuffer` on every call to `processSensorData`, even when `sensorId` is positive. This means that the old memory is not being deallocated, and the new memory is being allocated on top of the old memory, causing the heap to grow.\n\nThe `delete[] dataBuffer;` statement at the end of the function is indeed reached when `sensorId` is positive, but it's too late. By the time the `delete[]` statement is executed, the new memory has already been allocated, and the old memory is still being used. This is why the memory is not being freed.\n\nTo fix this, you should allocate the memory once and reuse it, as I mentioned earlier. Alternatively, you can use a smart pointer like `std::unique_ptr` or `std::shared_ptr` to manage the memory for you, which will automatically handle the deallocation when the object is no longer needed.\n\nHere's an example using `std::unique_ptr`",
